node.text:
Wish all of our friends at WNPA (Western National Parks Association) the happiest of birthdays. For 83 years they have helped to preserve, protect and tell the stories of the 70+ parks they work with daily. Thank you for supporting and loving parks over all of these years. You are the best. 
——
Thanks to @wnpa_1938 for sharing the goodness from Casa Grande Ruins National Monument where it all started. 
•
Today the Western National Parks Association turns 83 years old. From day one our goal has been "to aid the preservation and interpretation of Southwestern features of outstanding national interest." (That's word-for-word what the Secretary of the Interior gave WNPA, then known as Southwest Monuments Association (SWMA), to do when we were officially founded!)

Our organization seeks to help tell the parks' and the nation's story and support national parks across the west. From research initiatives to helping expand partner parks' programs and capabilities, we could not have done it during all 83 years without the contributions of all of our supporters.

We thank you all for helping to make our goals reality, whether you've been with us for decades or are just getting to know us now. How did you learn about WNPA and our work?

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Park Geek® in Yellowstone National Park with @ynpforever, @yellowstonenps, and @jeff.n.brenner. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
Bully. 
••••
Many thanks to Jeff  @jeff.n.brenner for the Yellowstone goodness. 
•
I’ve always had a very specific shot in my mind that I have never been able to get. I wanted a bison standing in an open area, during sunset, with Yellowstone’s geyser basin in the background. The sun needed to be in the perfect spot behind the billowing steam in order to catch the few seconds where a diffused golden haze fills the area in front. I had seen this phenomenon happen a couple times during past trips, but the moment is so fast that I’ve never had a good opportunity to capture it. After seeing this haze hit the landscape last summer, I logged the idea in my head, but didn’t actively pursue it since the elements of the photo seemed unrealistic to time correctly… not to mention I am rarely in this area during sunset.

During my trip in May, I was passing through the basin one afternoon and noticed a lone bison bull grazing alongside the river with the Grand Prismatic Spring out in the distance. I decided I’d go back to that spot an hour before sunset, hoping the bison would still be there. Thankfully, he was slow-moving and totally content with his little patch of grass, so I waited, and prayed that I’d luck out with that golden haze I saw the year before. Finally, the sun dropped past the steam and looked like it was gearing up to dust the basin in that sweet golden goodness. I propped myself behind a tree about 30yds from my bison and waited for that moment. Out of nowhere, a second bull came up from the riverbank and aggressively approached the one I was focused on. Initially, I expected a quick little sparring session, but it turned into an intense fight. Just as they began clashing, the light hit perfectly and the basin lit up in a way that didn’t seem like real life. In a matter of seconds, the shot I was hoping for turned into an experience that I never could’ve planned. It’s one of those experiences that made me fall in love with wildlife photography all over again. You can plan all you want, but nature tends to outdo any scene you set out to capture.
——-
#nationalparkgeek #bison #yellowstone

node.text:
Let’s finish out our Grand day at the Grand Canyon with more electrifying views. 

No matter the place you are, the Grand Canyon is one adventure you will not forget. Go find your canyon. 
•••••
Thanks to Tina  @naturesalbum for the sweet inspiration. 
•
The monsoon season that keeps on giving! We have been waiting for quite a while (meaning a few years) for a good set-up at the Grand Canyon for storms and lightning and when we saw it Tuesday and Wednesday we decided to try our luck. In a perfect world we were hoping to get some epic night time bolts striking in the canyon ... of course we didn't get that, ha, ha. On Wednesday though, we did get lucky enough to witness this stunning storm as it made it's way down the canyon toward us and then it was kind enough to toss out several photogenic bolts. We have included two photos taken on two separate cameras to show the close-up version of the lighting strikes and the wide version to show the full storm. We have said it many time before ... the canyon is pure magic!

node.text:
Continuing our Grand adventure, did you know you can see the Grand Canyon from below with a rafting trip? Get onboard to a life changing adventure. 
••••••
Thanks to Travis  @campoutsidephotos for the incredible ride. 
•
A few more shots from House Rapid on the Colorado River. There’s something that draws paddlers to whitewater. I’m not really sure what it is... When we cross a bridge we instinctively look at the water below. When we scout rapids, we stare at the water looking for a line. When we hit our lines we sometimes look back at the holes we miss or we just square up the boat and hit them head on. The size of these waves next to the 18ft Sotar Rafts is absolutely sobering. After reading about the recent tragedy in the Grand Canyon I am reminded how lucky we were to have a clean and safe trip as well as how powerful the water in the Grand Canyon is. #grandcanyon #nationalpark #whitewaterrafting #arizona #whitewaterkayaking #river #coloradoriver #rapid
